&gt; Theoretically, benchmarking could be useful for teams to justify their value — this is done frequently in UX research metrics, where you can buy different metric scores for lots of companies to compare yours (e.g., our site is in the 90th percentile of similar companies).
&gt; 
&gt; Doing something like that might be useful, and you could anonymize the data. No need to name a company (which avoids your concern in the other thread). People could simply look up “apparel retailers” or “quick service restaurants and see how their site compares to the peer group.
&gt; 
&gt; The question is — is that worth your time and effort? Personally, I’d love to punch in our site and maybe take it back to our product managers to help inform our conversations…but I wouldn’t pay for it.

&gt; you should write down every step that the user must do before they start to get value from the product (in other words, doing what they came there for).
&gt; 
&gt; Then mark each step as Red, Yellow, or green.
&gt; 
&gt; Red are things that are absolutely not related to delivering value.
&gt; 
&gt; Yellow are things that can conditionally add value
&gt; 
&gt; Green are things that are required for adding value.
&gt; 
&gt; Then go through the list and remove every one of the red things (or shift them elsewhere)
&gt; 
&gt; Then go through and see if the Yellow ones can be moved, or made better.
&gt; 
&gt; Green ones should be kept and made easier if possible
